utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: -- the incumbent congressman who didn't even show up to his own debate.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Do you think, you know, Bloomberg was a pretty good mayor, right?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well, compared to now, yeah.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah. You know, just a rock that you found at the bottom of a toilet.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Honestly, what -- did you see today? People are hiring private security --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: -- to protect themselves on the upper west side? Come on.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Well.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Anyway.

utterances.speaker: JESSE WATTERS, HOST
utterances.utterance: Is that what your Pilates teacher told you today?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: No, but he told me something else.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: So, Dana, since you're already talking, what do you -- do you think that somebody like him is going to make any headway?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I think that the headway he makes is by -- is within the party.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I don't think he goes to the front of the pack as their ultimate nominee, but can somebody like a Howard Schultz or Mike Bloomberg get the Democratic Party -- like, keep them from going so far left that --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: -- it's just unrecognizable.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: What do you think, Juan? Do you think -- you think he has a chance or will anybody listen to him? Or it's just like whoever is kind of Trumpian, charismatic, memorable is going to be -- who is going to be the nominee?

utterances.speaker: JUAN WILLIAMS, FOX NEWS HOST
utterances.utterance: Well, I think people like the fact that Mike Bloomberg is a thoughtful guy and he has a lot of money, obviously, so he can fund his own campaign. And he's going to get lots of platforms. Right there you saw him at St. Anne's that's already up in New Hampshire. So, no question he's going to be, you know, out there. And media attention in New York, he's known, the New York media likes him. So, but that's not the issue. The issue is whether or not a billionaire in an era of tremendous income inequality is in touch with the real issues that face the American people. I was looking up today, I've said -- something like, you know, was it, you know, huge number, 57 percent of Americans can't afford a $500 bill in 2019. And so, there's populism, the Trump side of it --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Who buys a $500 bill?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I don't know. Anyway, populism on the far right and populism on the far left, Bernie Sanders, Donald Trump. We've talked about this before. And I think he's out of touch with that. I mean, like for example, the criticism of Medicare for all which is coming from Kamala Harris. Well, guess what, most American support this.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Until they figure out how it works.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: And then they say what about, you know, can I keep this, whatever. But the principle, the bold idea that's starting a discussion is supported by most Americans, including most Republicans.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: But that is a half opinion, and the other half opinion which is never brought up is how do you pay for it. And once you get to that, the other opinion goes. Jesse, would you like to talk about Bloomberg or would you like to talk about Howie Schultz?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I'll do both, Greg.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Can I show you something?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Sure.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Anyway. It's this tape from Morning Joe.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: OK.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Watch what they did to Howie Schultz because they're trying to protect Kamala --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: OK.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: -- or Kamala.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: How much does an 18-ounce box of Cheerios cost?

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: An 18-ounce box of Cheerios? I don't know.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: Here's the deal. You ask us, you know, like the budget is for the V.A. We didn't ask you questions.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: I don't eat Cheerios, I'm sorry.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: OK. It's four bucks.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: Is it four bucks.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah, because she just looked it up on Google. She does not drink -- eat Cheerios for breakfast.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Well, as the reigning supermarket showdown champion, I was very disappointed in Schultz. And I bought some cereal today that cost $7.99. It was very expensive organic cereal.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You bought it --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I treat my body like it should be treated, right? Only the best for Watters. Here's what I think. What's happening right now in the Democratic Party is an intervention. And trust me, I know about interventions. It's happened a few times. I know when I see it. And the centrists are making the same arguments that conservatives have been making about socialism for decades. And this is why it stings so much, and the Democrat response is shut up, billionaire. That's all they have.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: And Schultz and Bloomberg are coming at the Democrats with genuine political fellowship. These are Trump haters. They want what's best for the country. And you think someone that ran the biggest city in the country, or ran one of the biggest companies in America knows a little something about supply and demands and basic economics. But instead, the Democrats don't argue the substance of their policies. They don't say this is how it's going to work, and this is why it's going to work, and this is how much it's going to cost. They just say you're mean for opposing me. So, it's bad politics and bad policy because you're ceding the entire middle of the country to Republicans, and Republicans don't even have to do anything. And if you look at the policy of it, to say I want to destroy a trillion dollar industry, put everybody out of work, 50 percent of the country gets their health insurance through their company, they like it. You take their plans away, it's going to be Armageddon.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: But you know what's interesting, they're -- Schultz is already having an effect because Kamala is already adjusting.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: She's on defense.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: She's on defense but she's changing her mind. She's going, you know, I'm not going to ditch the --

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Kind of.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: -- industry.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: But he never said that.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah, she did.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: All she said was --she never said that.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: She said eliminated.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: She said eliminated.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: But I think the big issue here, I'm surprised that you say this, Jesse, is the deficit has ballooned under Donald Trump. Where did Republicans come and say, oh, this is how we're going to pay for this huge tax cut and increase --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: The mainstream media completely loses it again, the reason for the latest meltdown, that's next.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Liberal media melting down after top intelligence officials testified on ISIS, North Korea, and Iran.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: President Trump and his intelligence chiefs are worlds apart on ISIS, Russia, and the border.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: This was essentially a public repudiation by his own people of Donald Trump's worldview.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: It was like these intelligence leaders we're describing a different planet than the one Donald Trump inhabits.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: His growing disparity between the ground truth that they presented and the planet that this president lives on.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: Where does the president get intelligence and foreign policy advice from?

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: Not agreeing with these conclusions is willful disregard of the facts.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: This is dangerous, is it?

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: It's incredibly dangerous.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: This is a dangerous thing.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: After that media freak out, the president calling his intel chiefs extremely passive and naive when it comes to Iran. All right, Dana. Well, I guess the president has made the media take the side of the intel agencies. They've never done that before. It's very doubtful.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: No. I'm sorry, aren't you forgetting 2003?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Oh, that's right. They're very critical back then. But what do you think is going on here with the president and his men at the top.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well, here's the thing. Like, I understand that the media -- like the story -- and we cover it all the time too. It's the story between -- about the president and the media, right? I'm actually melting down about the threats because these are -- it's like super serious. We're behind on the cyber war, especially from China and Russia. I look forward to this hearing every year because I want to know, like, what are the problems --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: You look forward to the intel hearing every year. Dana Perino, everybody. I do, too. But I just don't remember until the day before.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Look, and he also -- he said in his tweet that they should go back to school, and he's just throwing -- but, look, they work very hard for him every day.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Did you say throwing shade?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes, is that -- is that woke?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Oh, my gosh. You know, your Shultz and Christie interview all went to your head. Greg, what do you think is happening here? I mean, the president has always been very suspicious of the intel people after the WMD thing, and they've spied on his campaign, he didn't like that either.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: It's weird. The media is demanding that everybody agree. They can't be happy. They call it disparity but it's not lockstep. It's -- they want lockstep and if they don't see it then it's called disparity. They keep parsing over his tweets. They're like old guys on the beach with metal detectors hoping to find a bottle cap. Meanwhile, they overlook bigger stories that perhaps this is working. I mean, the fact that the good cop-bad cop thing that was going on with Syria, I think might be working. North Korea had a good cop-bad cop thing where people were disagreeing. That seems to be working. If you still do not believe there's any progress there. When you say that, oh, it's disparity that they're saying nothing is happening. It's actually better than it was last year and you have to admit it. And you can hold two ideas in your head. We are destroying ISIS. We will continue to destroy ISIS. It doesn't have to be, you know, the prison of two ideas. You said we destroyed ISIS, but they're still here. You can actually have both. We are destroying and continuing to destroy. The media wants you to be in their prison of two ideas. Let them stay in there. You have a free mind. You're smarter than they are. And you make more money than they are, Jesse.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Much smarter.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Go ahead. Take it away.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: I think that there's plenty of room for skepticism when it comes to what the intelligence community is saying, and the sourcing that these media outlets are using to push a certain agenda when it comes to foreign policy. However, when it comes to the threats that we do face, I was at a cybersecurity panel last week at foundation for defense of democracies, and they were saying, basically, with cyber, the good news is that were both -- both adversaries, United States, Russia, China, are both bad at responding and they're not -- and they're better at attacking, so that's their analysis. We have to get better at cyber. It's a very serious thing that's coming down the pike. There was talk of ways to respond to that. So while we're all, you know, fighting over who said what and who agrees with what, there are real things that are happening behind the scenes that we need good people to be doing. And so, when it comes to the ISIS thing, yeah, we've seen a number of ISIS attacks after the president has said directly they've been defeated. Is he talking about the territory? Yes. Does it mean ISIS is defeated all around the world? No. I got a press release today. Someone got arrested in the United States again for giving material support to ISIS. But that comes down to the ideology of Islamic radicalism and what our approaches to that.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Maybe the congresswoman from Minnesota can write a letter of support.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Maybe she can.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Juan, to Dana's point about the threats, there are a lot of really serious threats out there, but the president has been pretty strong on ISIS, on North Korea, on China --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: On Russia.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: -- he's been effective on those areas.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I'm listening to this defense coming from, at least, three of you, and I just think it's tissue thin. It's just -- but I guess you're desperate. I guess that's what --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Explain how it's tissue thin rather --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Because you have Trump's people -- these are Trump's people saying we are doing a realistic assessment and we all agree. It's not a matter of disagree. No, no. This is FBI, CIA, director of National Intelligence putting themselves on the line before you, the American people, and saying here's the reality. It's not what this guy is saying, not what Trump is saying. They don't mention the southern border, for example, as an immediate threat. No, no, no, they're talking about China and Russia increasingly working together against us.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Hang on. Hang on. You think about for a second, North Korea. He's going to go meet again. You say, wait a second, for what? And he says, well, things are better than ever. No, according to intelligence they're still intent on creating nuclear weapons. And how about Iran? Iran -- Trump is like, oh, yeah, Iran is terrible. Nope, intelligence -- they're not violating the terms of the Obama agreement, but you never hear this from Trump. It's like he's on a different planet and you guys are -- I don't want to hear it. I don't want to hear it.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Venezuela is now responding, saving that they are willing to cooperate. Must have been -- notepad.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Remember when Obama had the intel people cook the books on ISIS and say that, you know what, not that big of a threat anymore. And then, the rise of ISIS, he blamed the intel agencies for missing it. Remember when he weaponized the intel agencies to go after Donald Trump's campaign.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I tell you what, let's do a current affairs news show on Fox News Channel. Right now, today, you know what we learn? We learn that Trump is talking with Putin privately. He doesn't have a translator. Putin has a translator. Putin has aides. We don't even --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I'm going to translate it for you, Juan. Sour grapes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Oh, yeah. That's it.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: All right. Up next -- you're so safe. You can't stand being so safe.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: All right. You've never been right yet. Up next, insane video from the deep freeze in the Midwest, and the governor claiming the cold is making us too soft.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Ice, ice, baby. It's a deep-freeze in the Midwest. A polar vortex creating bone-chilling negative degree temperatures. It's so cold, rail cruise in Chicago had to light fires to keep the shrinking tracks connected. And check out this crazy video of our own Mike Tobin in Chicago earlier today. Yeah, that's boiling water thrown by Mike instantly turning to ice. Hundreds of schools are closed across a number of states, and in some places, the post office has stopped delivering the mail. But the governor of Kentucky, he's not having it. He says we're all getting too soft.

utterances.speaker: GOV. MATT BEVIN, R-KY.
utterances.utterance: Again, you know, now we cancel school for cold. I mean, --

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: Well, it's the deep-freeze. This is serious business.

utterances.speaker: BEVIN
utterances.utterance: Come on, now. I mean, there's no ice going with it or any snow. I mean, what happens to America? We're getting soft, Terry. We're getting soft. I've being only slightly facetious, but it does concern me a little bit that in America on this and any number of other fronts, we're sending messages to our young people that if life is hard, you can curl up in the fetal position somewhere in a warm place and just wait until it stops being hard. And that just isn't reality. It just isn't.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Wow, he's a hard man. Katie, what do you think? I saw Al Roker said that guy is a nitwit or something. The teacher of the year in Kentucky said, yeah, you go stand outside in this temperature --

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Back in my day, Juan, we walked to school uphill and back both ways.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: You're in Arizona.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: I grew up Flagstaff --

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: We have school off for an entire week one time.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I did, too. Pretty amazing.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, is that a sand storm.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: No, it's freezing. It's a snow storm.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: In Arizona?

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Snowy part of Arizona. People that knows this, but there is a part of Arizona that looks a lot like Colorado. We have a ski resort called Snow Ball. And it tends to get very cold there, but not negative 40 like in Chicago. And I've read a story today about how the penguins at the Cleveland Zoo had to be taken inside because it was so cold outside.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: I think the kids cannot go to school.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Wow. Jesse, incredible temperatures of 54 below, and International Falls, Minnesota, 52 below, in Minneapolis, in Chicago with the wind chill, 52 below. Are you going outside?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: No. There's only one way to beat the cold, Juan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Tell me.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Move.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I'd have everybody move. I wouldn't live there. If I lived there, I wouldn't stay there long. I'd go right to Florida where I belong. But if you do have to weather it out in a storm like this, I have some tips for staying warm. You guys want to hear them?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Sure.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Grow a beard. Does not apply to the ladies, just the men. Grow a beard.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Very sexist.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes. What if I couldn't grow a beard? Men who identify as women can grow beards.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: OK. Anybody that can grow a beard, you grow a beard. Get heat - - instead of oil to heat your home, do gas. It's cheaper. Always use jumper cables when you leave the house. And drive an SUV.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Did you get these off the internet?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: No, this is from my brain.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Get in your car and you drive, preferably, your SUV, because you need to drive an SUV because that's what's making the environment warmer because we need more warmth, obviously, to do that. Also, I'm taking back my sweater roll. Remember how I'm anti-sweater. I'm lifting the sweater ban. And if you want to layer up, you layer up.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: So, Dana, I can imagine that you as a little kid hanging out, anxious to hear school is close.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well, so, we -- to Matt Bevin's point, the governor of Kentucky, I think these decisions need to be made at a state and local basis, right? So our superintendent of school in Douglas County, Colorado, he would only close school if he could not get down his driveway in his tractor. It was like a quarter-mile. If he could get down in the tractor, then we all had to go to school. But the time -- I remember also we didn't have school for a week and it was because of temperatures like this.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, take a look. I mean --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: You studied up hard at home, right?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: We've watched the Prize is Right and Family Feud all night.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yes. So take a look at this tape here. Oh, it's a full -- OK, look at the full screen.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: We used to wear our pajamas inside out --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Here we go. As you can see from the full screen it says, we feel bad for kids nowadays. They get to see if school is closed on the internet, mobile devices, when people used to have to wait to see --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yeah. You'd wake up in the morning and then you come in, like, do we have -- is there any word yet? You have to wait for your local news. You watch the local news and, you know, there's suspense. The one thing I do worry about that we haven't paid enough attention to, I think, are the farmers and ranchers in these places that are trying to take care of their livestock. This is their livelihood. And they might end up having to do a disaster declaration.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Animals are great.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yeah. So, Greg, I imagine you would just say I'm not going to school.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Exactly. I grew up in the West Coast, but isn't it appropriate that the Kentucky governor is saying snowstorms are creating snowflakes.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Oh.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Ha, ha.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You can use that, Tomi Lahren. I didn't see snow until, maybe, I was 15. I went to Lake Tahoe skiing. I never -- I grew up on the West Coast. I got second degree burns.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I didn't see the beach until I was 16.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Wow.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: That's a great story.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Anyway, it's kind of tough to talk about whether - or a great show. We can talk about anything.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: I only complain one time a year and that's in the winter time.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Are you pulling your punches with your weather jokes?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Well, you know because you never - because like I don't want to seem like somebody who like - weather is - like there are people that are probably suffering, so I try to--

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: People dying.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes, so I try to be careful about making jokes about this.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: You don't have any Al Gore material.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No, I have nothing. I have nothing.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I'm disappointed.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Actually, I'm worried about my pipes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Your pipes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I don't want my pipes to burst. That happened last year.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Your voice.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: No.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No, no.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I have pipes in my building just exploded. OK, we'll go. And finally, I'm talking about the weather. Shut up. But just snowflakes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You know Katie (ph), you know what. Jesse gave me for Christmas.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: What? Snowflakes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: A snowflake suit. Yes.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Why didn't you wear it? Perfect for weather report.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No, it was a political statement. It wasn't a weather statement.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: But you should wear it now for the weather reporting you're doing.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Thank you, ma'am.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: So, well.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: The border wall debate, that's heating up again. As the President sends more troops to the border. Stay with us.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: The President sending several thousand more troops to the southern border as three more migrant caravans are heading towards the United States with one carrying roughly 12,000 people. And in Washington, a bipartisan group of lawmakers meeting today to try and nail down a plan for border security to avoid another potential government shutdown. President Trump warning if a wall is not part of the talks, "they're wasting their time". All right, Jesse, are we getting a wall in two weeks or not?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: We might get a fence.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Or a barrier.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I think it depends what you call it. I'm going to say something that might shock you. I believe I am more open minded than these Democrats.
